 1,974 prepolicy and 3,262 post-policy ads, and analyzed in 2023. A gold standard database was established by two coders who labeled 707 ads, which trained five natural language processing models to label the ads, covering content and target demographics. The descriptive statistics and multivariable logistic models were applied to analyze content before versus after policy implementation, both globally and by country. Results: Vertex AI emerged as the best natural language processing model with the highest F1 score of 0.87. There were significant decreases from pre- to post-policy implementation in the prevalence of labels of “Racial or Ethnic Identification” and “Ingredients: Natural” by 47% and 66%, respectively. Notable differences were identified from pre- to post-policy implementation in India, Mexico, and Germany. Conclusions: The study observed changes in skin-lightening product advertisement labels from pre- to post-policy implementation, both globally and within countries. Considering the influence of digital advertising on colorist norms, assessing digital ad policy changes is crucial for public health surveillance. This study presents a computational method to help monitor digital platform policies for consumer product advertisements that affect public health. © 2024 Elsevier Inc.","","depigmenting agent; advertising; Article; consumer; data mining; demographics; human; language processing; natural language processing; prevalence; propensity score; public health; public health surveillance; shade; South Africa; training; procedures; skin pigmentation; Advertising; Humans; Natural Language Processing; Skin Pigmentation","","Funding: The work presented in this manuscript was supported by the Strategic Training Initiative for the Prevention of Eating Disorders, based at the Harvard University T.H. Chan School of Public Health. The funding source was involved in various aspects of the study, including the design of the trial, data collection, analysis, and in